6.		Back to School Aromatherapy.

I first came in contact with the essential oils perhaps 15 
years ago. Their healing power awed and fascinated me from 
the start. Several years of study and experimentation with 
the essential oils followed. The founding of Nature's Gift 
Custom Aromatherapy Products followed. I am really delighted 
that the internet gives me a venue to learn from others, and 
to share what I've learned.

----- 

Back to school time in my family always triggered a round 
of new coughs and colds, as the children, especially the 
youngest, were exposed to germs from other neighborhoods.  
I wish when my children were school aged I had known about 
the wonders of aromatherapy, of the anti-bacterial and 
antiviral properties of some of the most common oils.

Some suggestions for beating the 'back to school' nasties 
in your house this Autumn.

One of the strongest antiviral and antibacterial Essential 
Oils is good old Lemon Oil (Citrus limon), cold pressed from 
the rind of the lemons. Don't buy the little 1/2 ounce 
bottle at your local health food store; you will often find 
Lemon Oil in bulk from many online suppliers. I don't 
recommend using lemon in 'skin blends' for massage, etc., 
but add a teaspoon or so of it to the washing machine (shake 
it up in a cup or so of water, first, and then pour it in) 
or pour a few drops on a cotton wash cloth and add it to the 
drier. Not only does it do a job on the nasties, but it 
leaves your clothes smelling 'cleaner than clean.' A few 
drops added to the dishpan while washing dishes, and added 
to the pan of water you wipe down countertops, floors, etc. 
will leave your kitchen germ free. I use lemon oil and water 
in a glass atomizer bottle for cleaning mirrors, the telephone 
receiver, around the bathroom sink, etc. Add a few drops to a
dishpan, or about a half teaspoon to a bucket of water. I do 
not recommend adding it to the dishwasher, since I'm not sure 
what effect it will have on plastic or rubber parts.

Another great germ killer is Tea Tree Oil, Melaleuca 
alternifolia, from Australia, or Manuka, Leptospermum 
scoparium from New Zealand. Different essential oils, 
the same effect on germs, viruses, molds and spores. I
prefer the Manuka because it has a slightly softer, less 
medicinal smell, but that is a matter of personal taste. 
Again, add to the water when cleaning up, or even add 
about four or five drops to a bath when you suspect 
someone might be coming down with a cold. (Make sure to 
stir the water thoroughly when adding EO's to a bath, 
since they don't disperse in the water.)

When it comes to homework time, sometimes even the most 
eager student has trouble settling down and concentrating.  
Research in Japan indicates that lemon oil dispersed in 
the air leads to better focus, fewer errors and heightened 
ability to concentrate.  Again, the spray bottle with a little
Lemon EO shaken in with water will do for an inexpensive room 
scenter. (Avoid spraying this on your antique wooden chair, 
the Essential Oil can do bad things to wood finishes.)

Another problem that seems epidemic nationwide is head lice.  
It happens to all of us, the nicest children from the nicest 
families in the nicest schools. There is anecdotal evidence 
that a shampoo with lavender, peppermint and tea tree 
essential oils added MAY help prevent an infestation. 
Adding a TOTAL of 10 drops of each essential oil per two
ounces of shampoo, and rinsing the hair with a vinegar/water 
rinse with five or six drops of the essential oil blend added 
to the rinse. If your child does bring home the dreaded note 
that lice have been found, a researcher on one of the 
Aromatherapy mailing lists has shared the following:

Shampoos are generally ineffective at killing lice and their 
eggs since they don't stay in contact long enough to be 
effective. It is better to use a base of 40% alcohol (vodka 
would do), 60% water and add EOs to that at a rate of 10 
drops to 2 ounces of the water/alcohol mix. Rub that into 
the scalp and leave on overnight then shampoo off in the 
morning. Then put a rinse through the hair using 2 mls of 
the same EO/ EO mix that you used originally added to half 
a pint of 50:50 vinegar and water. Repeat the whole process 
a week later. As to EOs to use, tea tree would work fairly
well but I would combine it with eucalyptus.  In working 
with small children, I prefer to use Eucalyptus Smithii, a 
gentler chemotype that is less apt to be irritating.  

If at all possible, I would rather try the above mixture, 
rather than the chemical shampoos that are sold for killing 
lice.  One still has to take a fine toothed comb to the nits, 
but the procedure above is generally effective.

Please be very careful about storing your Essential Oils if 
you have small children; many of them are toxic at very low 
doses if taken internally.

